overview.html.title: Overview
overview.html.body:
Overview
HiAI Engine runs above the operating system （OS） and below service applications. It provides unified standardized APIs for applications, shielding differences between OSs. It also provides the multi-node scheduling and multi-process management functions. HiAI Engine can set up and run service processes based on configuration files and summarize related statistics.
An engine in HiAI Engine is a specific service node. A service node represents a handling process. For example, a node can classify images, input image data, and output the classification prediction result of image data. Multiple engines form a graph. A graph manages its engines, as shown in  Figure 1.
Figure  1  Relationship between a graph and its engines
The connection between engine nodes is configured in the configuration file. The actual direction of data flows between nodes is implemented based on specific services. Once data is imported into the start node of a service, the entire compute process of the engines is started. The property configuration of a service node is the parameter required for running the node.

engine-process-execution.html.title: Engine Process Execution
engine-process-execution.html.body:
Engine Process Execution
The process execution depends on HiAI Engine provided by the neural-network processing unit （NPU） platform. HiAI Engine is a universal service process execution engine, consisting of:

HiAI Engine Agent: Runs on the host. The host refers to the X86 server, Windows PC, 3559, and AMD server connected to the device. They use the neural-network （NN） computing capability provided by the device to complete services. HiAI Engine Agent can:

Provide functional interfaces for the NPU chip.
Interact with the host app for controlling commands and processing data.
Implement interprocess communication （IPC） with the NPU.


HiAI Engine Manager:  Runs on the device. The device refers to the hardware device on which the NPU chip is installed. The device is connected to the host over the PCIe interface to provide the NN computing capability for the host. In the simulation environment, HiAI Engine Manager runs on the host. HiAI Engine Manager can:

Set up the service process according to the configuration file.
Destroy the service process and reclaim resources according to the command.
Provide the daemon process, responsible for the IPC function and the startup of software such as DVPP Executor, Framework, CCE, and Runtime on the device.



When a process is being executed, HiAI Engine schedules the task to the device through HiAI Engine Agent. After the execution is complete, the execution result is displayed in Mind Studio.
Figure 1  shows the interaction processes between HiAI Engine Agent and HiAI Engine Manager.
Figure  1  HiAI Engine flowchart

hiai-engine-development.html.title: HiAI Engine Development
hiai-engine-development.html.body:
HiAI Engine Development
You can use the HiAI Engine programming framework for development in either of the following ways:

Default project: Mind Studio provides a graphical drag-and-drop interface for orchestrating AI applications. In this mode, the framework code is automatically generated when users perform graphical drag-and-drop on Mind Studio, with the corresponding Makefile generated at the same time. The code structure is relatively fixed, that is, engine process orchestration.
Custom project: Indicates a user-defined project. This mode does not provide a graphical orchestration interface. The framework code, Makefile, and compilation scripts are developed by users. In this mode, the code structure is flexible and can be customized by users.

default-project-development.html.title: Default Project Development
default-project-development.html.body:
Default Project Development
The default Mind Engine project of Mind Studio provides visualized drag-and-drop programming of AI engines and automatic generation technology of algorithm code, greatly reducing the difficulty for developers. Service developers can orchestrate and run service processes by dragging graphical service nodes, connecting service nodes, and editing service node properties to achieve zero coding of service process orchestration.
For details about the development process and example of a default project, see chapter "Building the First Machine Learning App" in the  Mind Studio Quick Start.

Importing Sample Project Code
The following uses the sample code originally contained in the Mind Studio device development kit （DDK） as an example for development illustration.

Copy the HiAI Engine sample code in the DDK to the new custom project  Custom_Engine.
Log in to the Mind Studio server as the Mind Studio installation user, and run the following command to copy the code of the hiaiengine sample project to the custom project:
cp -rf $HOME/tools/che/ddk/ddk/sample/hiaiengine/* /projects/Custom_Engine/

 NOTE:   

$HOME/tools is the default installation path of the DDK.  
Custom_Engine  is the name of a custom engine project created in the scenario where ASIC is used. If Atlas DK is used, replace  Custom_Engine  with  Custom_Engine_AtlasDK.  
You can also choose  Local（Web Server）  from the  Source Code From  drop-down list box , choose  $HOME/tools/che/ddk > ddk > sample > hiaiengine  from  Local File Path  to import a hiaiengine sample project when creating a project.

offline-model-conversion.html.title: Offline Model Conversion
offline-model-conversion.html.body:
Offline Model Conversion
To convert an external network model into the Da Vinci model supported by Huawei NPU, use either of the following methods:

Use the offline model conversion function provided by Mind Studio to convert models.
Use the background command to convert offline models.

The following describes these two methods in detail.
Using Mind Studio

Right-click the custom engine project and choose  Convert Model  from the shortcut menu, or choose  Tools > Convert Model  from the menu bar. The model conversion window is displayed, as shown in  Figure 1.
Figure  1  Offline model conversion

 NOTE:   

If you use a custom project to convert a model, you need to disable input image preprocessing. For details about the quantization parameter description, see section "Reference" in the  Mind Studio Basic Operations.  
This document uses the ResNet-18 network model as an example to describe how to obtain the model file.  


In the  Model File  and  Weight File  drop-down list boxes, select the model file and weight file of the model to be converted, and click  ok.
For details about other parameters for offline model conversion, see chapter "Model Management" in the  Mind Studio Basic Operations.

After the model is converted successfully, you can view the converted offline model by choosing  model-zoo  >  offline-model, as shown in  Figure 2.
Figure  2  Converted offline model
In the  Model Zoo Explorer window, select a converted offline model, for example,  device  >  resnet18.om  （in this example, the target is an ASIC or Atlas DK project）. Right-click  Copy Path  . Paste the path on the background server where Mind Studio is located. Then you can obtain the path of the current model file.

Copy the offline model file to the current custom project.
cp $HOME/tools/che/model-zoo/offline-model/resnet18/device/resnet18.om /projects/Custom_Engine/

 NOTE:$HOME/tools/che/model-zoo/offline-model/resnet18/device/resnet18.om  is the path of the converted model file.  $HOME/tools  is the default installation path of the DDK.Custom_Engine  is the name of the custom project.  

See  Figure 3.
Figure  3  Adding the converted offline model file


Using the Background Command

Save the model file and weight file of the model to be converted to the project directory. For example, place the  resnet18.caffemodel  and  resnet18.prototxt files in the  /projects/Custom_Engine/  directory of the Mind Studio server.
Run the following command in the  Custom_Engine  directory as the Mind Studio installation user to convert an external network model to the Da Vinci model:
# /projects/uihost/bin/omg --model=resnet18.prototxt --weight=resnet18.caffemodel --framework=0  --output=resnet18
Where,

--model: relative path of the  resnet18.prototxt file
--weight: relative path of the  resnet18.caffemodel  file
--framework: original framework type

0: Caffe
1: Caffe 2
2: MXNet
3: TensorFlow


--output: name of the output model file, which can be customized


After the command is executed, a model file whose name is suffixed with  .om  is generated, for example,  resnet18.om.

 NOTE:To use a custom project to convert a model, you need to disable the AIPP parameter. For details about how to use the AIPP and quantization parameters in the OMG command, see section "Convert Model Using the omg Command" in the  Ascend 310 Mind Studio Basic Operations.

engine-connection-configuration.html.body:
Engine Connection Configuration
The parameters related to engines and the connection between engine ports are configured in graphs. In the following example, the connection configuration file is  config/sample.prototxt, and the model name in  value  of  model_path  in FrameworkerEngine is changed to the name of the model file generated in  Offline Model Conversion.  Engine Connection Configuration  shows a configuration example. In the AtlasDK scenario, the connection configuration file is config/sample_mini.prototxt.
Figure  1  Configuration example of the process connection file
In this example, the graph ID is  100. The  engines  parameter indicates the property configuration of each engine. The  connects  parameter indicates the connection relationship between engines. The parameter  side  under  engines  indicates the running target of the engine.

 NOTE:Engines can be connected across graphs. You can configure the graph ID of the receive end in  target_port_id  under  connects. In the complex scenario where multiple Ascend 310 chips are used, to enable the models to run on different Ascend 310 chips （try to implement inference of the same models on the same Ascend 310 chip to reduce unnecessary memory consumption）, you can connect engines across graphs.

asic-scenario-0.html.body:
ASIC Scenario
You can compile a custom project in either of the following ways:

You do not need to compile Makefile, while you can compile a project on the compilation GUI available on Mind Studio.
Compile Makefile and run the background command to compile a project.

The following describes these two methods in detail.
Compiling a Project on Mind Studio
In this compilation mode, you do not need to compile Makefile. The detailed procedure is as follows:

Select the project whose project structure needs to be configured, and then choose  Build > Edit Build Configuration. The window for configuring a custom project is displayed, as shown in  Figure 1.
Figure  1  Configuration window for a custom project

Configure a custom project.
The custom configuration project consists of three parts:  Main, Host, and  Device.
Each .so file needs to be configured on the corresponding tab page based on the  side  value of each engine in the  sample.prototxt file.
Table 1  describes the  Main, Host, and  Device  parameters.
Table  1  Configuration description

Configuration Item

Description



Main

Indicates the implementation file of the engine on the Main tab page. Select the .cpp execution file, that is, the main.cpp file.
After the configuration is saved, the CMakeLists.txt file is generated in the build folder under the root directory of the project.
If the compilation is successful, the main file is generated in the out folder.


Host

Add the engine that needs to run on the host and enter the engine name. The name cannot be the same as the project name. (You can click  next to HOST_PARAM to add an engine or click  on the right of the corresponding engine to delete an engine.)
Each host engine saves the configuration and generates a folder with the same name as the engine name, which contains the CMakeLists.txt file in the build folder under the root directory of the project.
If the compilation is successful, the .so file with the same name as the engine name is generated in the out folder.


Device

Add the engine that needs to run on the device and enter the engine name. The name cannot be the same as the project name. (You can click  next to Device_PARAM to add an engine or click  on the right of the corresponding engine to delete an engine.)
Each device engine saves the configuration and generates a folder with the same name as the engine name, which contains the CMakeLists.txt file in the build folder under the root directory of the project.
If the compilation is successful, the .so file with the same name as the engine name is generated in the out folder.






 NOTE:The .so file needs to be signed to avoid being tampered with. The signing method is as follows:  

Call the RSA_generate_key interface of the OpenSSL tool to generate the public key  pub.pem  and the private key  pri.pem. The recommended key length is greater than or equal to 2048 bits  
Use the private key to sign the .so file using the SHA256 algorithm to generate the  .so.signature  file, which is stored in the same directory as the original .so file.  
Call the SetPublicKeyForSignatureEncryption interface to transfer the public key to HiAI Engine. For details about the APIs, see the  HiAI Engine API Reference.  


Which of the three tab pages is configured depends on which side the .so file of the engine needs to be stored. In this example, an ASIC project is used. SrcEngine and DestEngine run on the host. FrameworkerEngine runs on the device. The following figure shows the compilation configuration example.
Figure  2  Configuration example on the  Main  tab page
Click  Build Options  in  Figure 2. A dialog box is displayed, as shown in  Figure 3.

 NOTE:   

If you do not click  Build Options  or do not configure the configuration items in the  Build Options  configuration window, the default values are used during compilation.  
In  Build Options, you need to set  Include Path  on the  Main  and  Device  tab pages, for example,  /projects/Custom_Engine.  


Figure  3  Build Options
Table 2  describes the parameters on each tab page of the  Build Options configuration window.
Table  2  Parameter description for Build Options configuration

Build Options Configuration Item

Description



Automatically regenerate CMakeLists.txt

This check box is selected by default.
If this check box is selected, the CMakeLists.txt file is automatically overwritten each time the configuration is saved. (If the Makefile is modified, the CMakeLists.txt file will also be overwritten.)If this check box is deselected, the CMakeLists.txt file is not automatically overwritten each time the configuration is saved.


C++ Standard

C++ standard. The options are as follows:
C++ 11C++ 98
The default setting is C++ 11.


Debug Flags

Compilation mode. The options are as follows:
DebugRelease
The default setting is Debug.


Cpp Flags

Compilation option, which is configured by users.


Link Library

Referenced link library, which can be configured by users.
Linked dynamic library, corresponding to the value of -l in the compilation command.


Lib Path

Link library path. Currently, the default path is used. You can add configuration.
Dynamic library search path, corresponding to the value of -L in the compilation command.


Include Path

Header file path. Currently, the default path is used. You can add configuration.
Header file search path, corresponding to the value of -I in the compilation command.





Figure 4  shows the configuration example of the  Host  tab page.
Figure  4  Configuring SrcEngine on the Host tab page
Click    next to HOST_PARAM to add a DestEngine, as shown in  Figure 5.
Figure  5  Configuring DestEngine on the Host tab page
Figure 6  shows the configuration example of the  Device  tab page.
Figure  6  Configuration of the Device tab page

After the configuration is complete, click  Save  to save the project structure configuration. Click  Build  or choose  Build > Build > Project Name  on the menu bar to compile the project structure.
The project structure configuration can be saved in either of the following ways:

In the  Build Options  window, if  Automatically regenerate CMakeLists.txt  is selected, the  build  window will display the generation information of CMakeLists.txt files, and the  build  folder that stores the CMakeLists.txt files is automatically generated in the root directory of the project, as shown in  Figure 7.
Figure  7  Project directory example

If  Automatically regenerate CMakeLists.txt  in the  Build Options  window is deselected:

If the  build folder does not exist in the root directory of the project or the  build folder in the root directory of the project does not contain the CMakeLists.txt  file, the  build folder containing the  CMakeLists.txt  file is automatically generated, as shown in  Figure 7.
If the  build  folder containing the CMakeLists.txt  file exists in the root directory of the project, the  Automatically regenerate CMakeLists.txt  dialog box is displayed, as shown in  Figure 8.
Figure  8  Automatically regenerate CMakeLists.txt dialog box
If you click  OK, the original  CMakeLists.txt file is overwritten.
If you click  Cancel, the  CMakeLists.txt  file in the current project directory is used for compilation, and no more  CMakeLists.txt file is generated.




After the project compilation is complete, the  build  window displays the result, as shown in  Figure 9.
Figure  9  Compilation output window
After the compilation is successful, the out  folder is generated in the project root directory, as shown in  Figure 10.
Figure  10  out folder after compilation
The  Custom_Engine  file in the  out folder is the executable file generated by the Main Engine.

 NOTE:   

The folders and files that are not selected by the Main Engine, Host Engines, and Device Engines in the project are skipped during compilation.  
If a project that has not been configured is compiled in one-click mode, the  build folder that exists in the root directory of the project is directly used to compile the project if the folder contains the  CMakeLists.txt file. Otherwise, the project is compiled using the selected configuration.  
If a project is renamed, you need to change the path value of  Files  on the  Main,  Host, and  Device tab pages. If the previous configuration is run, the generator generates an invalid project with the original project name based on the path value in the original  Files.  




Running the Background Command to Compile a Project

Modify Makefile.
Makefile has been provided in the root directory of the sample project. You can modify Makefile based on the sample. The path of Makefile is  Custom_Engine/Makefile.

Change the value of  sample/hiaiengine  in  TOPDIR  and  LOCAL_DIR  to the project name. The project name is user-defined during project creation, for example,  Custom_Engine, as shown in  Figure 11.
Figure  11  Modifying the project name in Makefile
LOCAL_MODULE_NAME  is the name of the executable file that is generated. You can customize it. For example, you can change it to  Custom_Engine.

Change the value of  local_shared_libs_dirs to the actual link library /uihost/lib  （configured in  Configuration Library Information and Environment Variable）, as shown in  Figure 12.
Figure  12  Modifying the library path in Makefile
Makefile is parsed as follows:
TOPDIR      := $(patsubst %/Custom_Engine,%,$(CURDIR))
LOCAL_DIR  := $(TOPDIR)/Custom_Engine
INCLUDE_DIR := $(TOPDIR)/include
LOCAL_MODULE_NAME := Custom_Engine
CC_FLAGS := -std=c++11
local_src_files := \  # Source file related to compilation
    $(LOCAL_DIR)/main.cpp \
    $(LOCAL_DIR)/impl/impl_engines.cpp \
    $(LOCAL_DIR)/impl/ai_model_engine.cpp \
local_inc_dirs := \   # Header file related to compilation
    $(LOCAL_DIR) \
    $(INCLUDE_DIR)/inc \
    $(INCLUDE_DIR)/third_party/protobuf/include \
    $(INCLUDE_DIR)/third_party/cereal/include \
    $(INCLUDE_DIR)/libc_sec/include
local_shared_libs_dirs := \ # Path of the library to be linked, corresponding to Lib Path on the GUI.
    $(TOPDIR)/uihost/lib \
local_shared_libs := \ # DLL to be linked, corresponding to Link Library on the GUI
    hiai_server_cmodel \
    hiai_common \
    matrix_cmodel \
    pthread \
    protobuf \
include ./cc_rule.mk # Contains other makefiles.
The cc_rule.mk file is parsed as follows:
Q := @
exist = $(shell if [ -f $(../../toolchains/aarch64-linux-gcc6.3/bin/aarch64-linux-gnu-g++) ]; then echo "exist"; else echo "notexist"; fi;)
ifeq ($(exist), exist)
#exit 0
CPP := g++
else
exit 0
endif
FULL_SRC_FILES        := $(local_src_files)
FULL_INC_DIRS         := $(foreach inc_dir, $(local_inc_dirs), -I$(inc_dir))
SHARED_LIBRARIES      := $(foreach shared_lib, $(local_shared_libs), -l$(shared_lib))
SHARED_LIBRARIES_DIRS := $(foreach shared_lib_dir, $(local_shared_libs_dirs), -L$(shared_lib_dir) -Wl,-rpath-link,$(shared_lib_dir))
LOCAL_OBJ_PATH        := $(LOCAL_DIR)/out # Defines the compilation output path.
LOCAL_LIBRARY         := $(LOCAL_OBJ_PATH)/$(LOCAL_MODULE_NAME)
FULL_C_SRCS           := $(filter %.c,$(FULL_SRC_FILES))
FULL_C_OBJS           := $(patsubst $(LOCAL_DIR)/%.c,$(LOCAL_OBJ_PATH)/%.o, $(FULL_C_SRCS))
FULL_CPP_SRCS         := $(filter %.cpp,$(FULL_SRC_FILES))
FULL_CPP_OBJS         := $(patsubst $(LOCAL_DIR)/%.cpp,$(LOCAL_OBJ_PATH)/%.o, $(FULL_CPP_SRCS))
all: do_pre_build do_build
do_pre_build:
 $(Q)echo - do [$@]
 $(Q)mkdir -p $(LOCAL_OBJ_PATH)
do_build: $(LOCAL_LIBRARY) | do_pre_build
 $(Q)echo - do [$@]
# $(Q)rm -rf $(LOCAL_OBJ_PATH)
$(LOCAL_LIBRARY): $(FULL_C_OBJS) $(FULL_CPP_OBJS) | do_pre_build
 $(Q)echo [LD] $@
 $(Q)$(CPP) $(CC_FLAGS) -o $(LOCAL_LIBRARY) $(FULL_C_OBJS) $(FULL_CPP_OBJS) -Wl,--whole-archive  -Wl,--no-whole-archive -Wl,--start-group  -Wl,--end-group $(SHARED_LIBRARIES_DIRS) $(SHARED_LIBRARIES)
$(FULL_C_OBJS): $(LOCAL_OBJ_PATH)/%.o : $(LOCAL_DIR)/%.c  | do_pre_build
 $(Q)echo [CC] $@
 $(Q)mkdir -p $(dir $@)
 $(Q)$(CPP) $(CC_FLAGS)  $(FULL_INC_DIRS) -c $


Go to the  /projects/Custom_Engine  directory and run the  make -j  command. After the compilation is successful, the executable program of the project is generated in the  Custom_Engine/out  directory, as shown in  Figure 13.
Figure  13  out folder

introduction-4.html.title: Introduction
introduction-4.html.body:
Introduction
HiAI Engine runs above the operating system （OS） and below service applications. It provides unified standard interfaces for apps, shielding differences between OSs. It also provides multi-node scheduling and multi-process management. In addition, HiAI Engine can set up and run service processes based on configuration files and summarize statistics.
The overall logic of the HiAI Engine solution consists of two parts: HiAI Engine Agent （which runs on the host） and HiAI Engine Manager (which generally runs on the device, but runs on the host in the simulation environment).

 NOTE:   

The host refers to the X86 server, ARM server, or Windows PC connected to the device. The host uses the neural-network （NN） computing capability provided by the device to complete services.  
The device refers to the hardware device configured with the Ascend 310 chip. The device connects to the host over the PCIe interface to provide the NN computing capability for the host.  



HiAI Engine Agent:

Provides Ascend 310 functional APIs.
Interacts with the host apps for controlling commands and processing data.
Performs interprocess communication （IPC） with the device.


HiAI Engine Manager:

Creates service processes according to the configuration files.
Destroys service processes and reclaims resources according to commands.
Provides daemon processes for the IPC function and the startup of software such as the DVPP executor and Framework on the device.

 NOTE:   

Digital vision pre-processing （DVPP） implements video encoding and decoding, JPEG encoding and decoding, PNG decoding, and visual pre-processing.  
Framework uses a deep learning framework and converts open-source framework models such as Caffe and TensorFlow models into models supported by Mind Studio.  






You can view the API definition files in  ddk/include/inc/hiaiengine  in the installation directory of the DDK. If you install both Mind Studio and the DDK in boot installation mode, you can log in to the Mind Studio server as the Mind Studio installation user and view the API definition files in  ~/tools/che/ddk/ddk/include/inc/hiaiengine. For details about the mapping between the definition files and the APIs, see the API description.

HIAIMemory::HIAI_DMalloc （C++ Dedicated）
Allocates memory blocks through the HiAI interface to support efficient data transmission. This API is defined in  ai_memory.h.
Application scenario:
Under the HiAI Engine framework, this API is used to transfer big data from the host to the device. It must be used together with  Macro: HIAI_REGISTER_SERIALIZE_FUNC.
For example, a 1080p or 4K image needs to be sent to the device. If the transmission performance needs to be improved, you must register the structure serialization and deserialization functions through HIAI_REGISTER_SERIALIZE_FUNC. In addition, the big data block memory is allocated through the HIAI_DMalloc interface. This greatly improves the transmission performance.

 NOTE:   

This API deals with the big data transfer between the host and device. You are advised not to use it as a common malloc function.  
For the sake of performance, this API pre-allocates memory. The actual memory size is different from the allocated memory size. The running time of this API may also change.  
If the SendData API is used to send data after the memory is allocated, the framework will incorporate the allocated memory into the memory pool for unified management. After the program runs, the memory is released.  
If the huge page memory is allocated when HIAI_DMalloc is called, the block memory is not included in the memory pool after SendData ends. In this case, you need to manually call HIAI_DFree to release the memory.  
When the HiAI interface is used to allocate memory, the maximum memory size that can be allocated is 256 KB–128 MB.

graph-setpublickeyforsignatureencryption.title: Graph::SetPublicKeyForSignatureEncryption
graph-setpublickeyforsignatureencryption.body:
Graph::SetPublicKeyForSignatureEncryption
This API is used to set the public key, which is used to verify the digital signature of the *.so file to be loaded to HiAI Engine on the device. This API must be called before a graph is created. This API is defined in  graph.h.
The digital signature algorithm is  SHA256withRSA. This component provides only the digital signature verification function. You need to sign the required .so file based on the algorithm. The path for storing the signature file on the host must be in the same directory as the .so file. The name of the signature file is Name of the .so file+ .signature. For example, if the name of the .so file is libhosttodevice.so, then the name of the signature file is  libhosttodevice.so.signature.

 CAUTION:If Graph::SetPublicKeyForSignatureEncryption is not called or the return value is not  HIAI_OK, the public key cannot be set in HiAI Engine and the signature verification mechanism will not be started on the device. Therefore, the *.so file that may be tampered with cannot be identified by using the digital signature.
